{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659913"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21085"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91111"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of the spinal cord is examined under light microscopy. Large neurones with abundant cytoplasm and prominent Nissl substance are observed in the anterior horn.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of these neurones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coordinate autonomic functions","Modulate pain sensation pathways","Relay sensory information to the brain","Innervate skeletal muscle fibres","Process proprioceptive information"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neurones described in the stem are alpha motor neurones located in the anterior (ventral) horn of the spinal cord. Their primary function is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einnervate skeletal muscle fibres\u003C/strong\u003E, forming neuromuscular junctions that control voluntary movement. These neurones are characterised by their large cell bodies, prominent Nissl substance (rough endoplasmic reticulum), and a large nucleus with a visible nucleolus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelay sensory information to the brain\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of sensory neurones in the dorsal root ganglia and ascending pathways, not motor neurones in the anterior horn.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinate autonomic functions\u003C/strong\u003E - Autonomic functions are controlled by neurones in the intermediolateral cell column (sympathetic) or sacral parasympathetic nuclei, not by anterior horn cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcess proprioceptive information\u003C/strong\u003E - Proprioceptive information is processed by neurones in the dorsal horn and Clarke\u0027s nucleus, not by anterior horn motor neurones.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModulate pain sensation pathways\u003C/strong\u003E - Pain modulation occurs primarily in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord, not in the anterior horn where motor neurones are located.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior horn motor neurones receive inputs from descending motor pathways and local interneurones, and their axons exit the spinal cord via the ventral roots to innervate skeletal muscles throughout the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Motor neurones in the anterior horn of the spinal cord have large cell bodies with prominent Nissl substance.","The anterior horn of the spinal cord contains alpha motor neurones that innervate skeletal muscle.","Motor neurones are characterised by a large nucleus with a prominent nucleolus and abundant rough endoplasmic reticulum in the cytoplasm."],"references":["Nervous Tissue: Spinal Cord Motor Neuron. Flikr. Image accessed under CC0 1.0 license: https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/146824358@N03/41850849912/","Young B, O\u0027Dowd G, Woodford P. Wheater\u0027s functional histology. 7th ed. London: Churchill Livingstone; 2025."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21820"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21820"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EZsViaPLDq05bKfOQDIhKsRHHxjBGb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EZsViaPLDq05bKfOQDIhKsRHHxjBGb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":846}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T11:00:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T11:01:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","p